But if you do that excessively--
in the whole no-carb world that

00:16:12.040 --> 00:16:12.857 align:middle line:90%
we live in--

00:16:12.857 --> 00:16:15.190 align:middle line:84%
that carbs have been deemed
so bad for us, from Atkins--

00:16:15.190 --> 00:16:16.300 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But the
brain needs those.

00:16:16.300 --> 00:16:18.130 align:middle line:84%
Just with serotonin
production, don't we need it?

00:16:18.130 --> 00:16:19.660 align:middle line:84%
>>DOUILLARD: The
brain needs sugar.

00:16:19.660 --> 00:16:21.370 align:middle line:90%
They're long-lasting sugars.

00:16:21.370 --> 00:16:22.500 align:middle line:90%
They're very important.

00:16:22.500 --> 00:16:24.123 align:middle line:84%
And see, if you
don't have any carbs,

00:16:24.123 --> 00:16:26.290 align:middle line:84%
your body's going to get
its energy from fat, right?

00:16:26.290 --> 00:16:26.560 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mm-hm.

00:16:26.560 --> 00:16:27.910 align:middle line:84%
>>DOUILLARD: And we lose weight,
and everybody feels great.

00:16:27.910 --> 00:16:29.170 align:middle line:90%
That was the Atkins model.

00:16:29.170 --> 00:16:29.485 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Happy.

00:16:29.485 --> 00:16:29.800 align:middle line:90%
Mm-hm.

00:16:29.800 --> 00:16:31.217 align:middle line:84%
>>DOUILLARD: The
problem with that

00:16:31.217 --> 00:16:33.700 align:middle line:84%
is that when you go
into fat metabolism,

00:16:33.700 --> 00:16:37.060 align:middle line:84%
the body creates a lot of
ketones, which is actually

00:16:37.060 --> 00:16:40.900 align:middle line:84%
a chemical that your body has
to process through the kidneys.

00:16:40.900 --> 00:16:46.270 align:middle line:84%
And long-term, low carbohydrate,
high protein, high fat diets

00:16:46.270 --> 00:16:47.662 align:middle line:84%
can actually damage
your kidneys.

00:16:47.662 --> 00:16:49.120 align:middle line:84%
In the end, the
last thing you want

00:16:49.120 --> 00:16:52.000 align:middle line:84%
to do in the name of good health
is create another problem.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.670 align:middle line:84%
And that's what we do when
we go into these extreme ways

00:16:54.670 --> 00:16:54.760 align:middle line:90%
of eating.

00:16:54.760 --> 00:16:56.980 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Wasn't that the case
with some of the Atkins diet?

00:16:56.980 --> 00:16:58.010 align:middle line:84%
>>DOUILLARD: That's
exactly what happened.

00:16:58.010 --> 00:16:59.480 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: People had
a lot of that problem.

00:16:59.480 --> 00:17:00.030 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:17:00.030 --> 00:17:00.440 align:middle line:90%
Gall bladder.

00:17:00.440 --> 00:17:00.910 align:middle line:90%
>>DOUILLARD: Yep.

00:17:00.910 --> 00:17:02.410 align:middle line:84%
One of the main reasons
why it fell out of favor

00:17:02.410 --> 00:17:04.827 align:middle line:84%
was because there was a lot
of reports of kidney problems,

00:17:04.827 --> 00:17:08.560 align:middle line:84%
and that scares people, and
it should, and rightfully so.

00:17:08.560 --> 00:17:10.839 align:middle line:90%
So it's about balance.

00:17:10.839 --> 00:17:12.839 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: It all comes
back to that, doesn't it?

00:17:12.839 --> 00:17:13.000 align:middle line:90%
>>DOUILLARD: Right.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:14.619 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But we
are out of balance.

00:17:14.619 --> 00:17:15.109 align:middle line:84%
>>DOUILLARD: We
are out of balance.

00:17:15.109 --> 00:17:17.260 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Because we're
following every fad.

00:17:17.260 --> 00:17:20.410 align:middle line:84%
If we tend to follow whatever
the latest gurus, health

00:17:20.410 --> 00:17:23.087 align:middle line:84%
guru, food diet
guru's book is, we

00:17:23.087 --> 00:17:25.420 align:middle line:84%
are going to be out of balance
for the most part, right?

00:17:25.420 --> 00:17:28.750 align:middle line:84%
>>DOUILLARD: Because
these diets tend to just--

00:17:28.750 --> 00:17:32.350 align:middle line:90%
they last for about five years.

00:17:32.350 --> 00:17:36.010 align:middle line:84%
Years ago, when we
had the Pritikin diet,

00:17:36.010 --> 00:17:38.418 align:middle line:84%
Pritikin basically said, you
can eat 80% carbohydrates,

00:17:38.418 --> 00:17:40.210 align:middle line:84%
and lose weight, feel
good, and everything.

00:17:40.210 --> 00:17:41.210 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah, no fats.

00:17:41.210 --> 00:17:43.020 align:middle line:84%
>>DOUILLARD: So then,
all of a sudden,

00:17:43.020 --> 00:17:44.530 align:middle line:84%
everybody's blood sugar
started going crazy

00:17:44.530 --> 00:17:45.760 align:middle line:84%
because they're eating
lots of sugars--

00:17:45.760 --> 00:17:46.560 align:middle line:90%
80% carbohydrates.

00:17:46.560 --> 00:17:48.160 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Per capita,
didn't we go up

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:51.490 align:middle line:84%
something like 12% over
that decade where that was

00:17:51.490 --> 00:17:52.900 align:middle line:90%
at the top of the food pyramid?

00:17:52.900 --> 00:17:53.590 align:middle line:90%
>>DOUILLARD: Right, exactly.

00:17:53.590 --> 00:17:54.890 align:middle line:84%
And it wasn't
really his message.

00:17:54.890 --> 00:17:56.348 align:middle line:84%
His message was
more balanced food.

00:17:56.348 --> 00:17:59.980 align:middle line:84%
But we hear 80% carbs, and the
food industry hears 80% carbs,

00:17:59.980 --> 00:18:02.127 align:middle line:84%
it becomes short-chain,
quick, fast-moving carbs

00:18:02.127 --> 00:18:03.210 align:middle line:90%
injected into blood sugar.

00:18:03.210 --> 00:18:04.420 align:middle line:90%
And then we have hypoglycemia.

00:18:04.420 --> 00:18:04.750 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:18:04.750 --> 00:18:06.333 align:middle line:84%
>>DOUILLARD: And
then the hypoglycemia

00:18:06.333 --> 00:18:09.460 align:middle line:84%
created stress, which caused
cholesterol levels to rise

00:18:09.460 --> 00:18:10.510 align:middle line:90%
and shoot up like crazy.

00:18:10.510 --> 00:18:12.970 align:middle line:84%
And then we blamed
it on animal fats.

00:18:12.970 --> 00:18:16.112 align:middle line:84%
So then margarine and all these
crazy fad diets came into play.

00:18:16.112 --> 00:18:18.070 align:middle line:84%
And then we started
saying, hey, you know what?

00:18:18.070 --> 00:18:20.900 align:middle line:84%
The blood sugar's wacky, this
is a real serious problem,

00:18:20.900 --> 00:18:23.020 align:middle line:84%
so we should eat
six meals a day.

00:18:23.020 --> 00:18:25.120 align:middle line:90%
Now America started grazing.

00:18:25.120 --> 00:18:27.820 align:middle line:84%
Every two to three hours, we're
eating little, tiny meals.

00:18:27.820 --> 00:18:29.780 align:middle line:90%
Now let me ask you something.

00:18:29.780 --> 00:18:31.570 align:middle line:84%
If you want your
body to burn fat,

00:18:31.570 --> 00:18:33.410 align:middle line:84%
it makes good sense
to give it a reason.

00:18:33.410 --> 00:18:36.100 align:middle line:84%
So if you have breakfast, snack,
lunch, snack, supper, snack,

00:18:36.100 --> 00:18:37.572 align:middle line:84%
when does your
body burn its fat?

00:18:37.572 --> 00:18:39.030 align:middle line:84%
Compared to if you
have breakfast--

00:18:39.030 --> 00:18:40.180 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: When you're sleeping?

00:18:40.180 --> 00:18:40.570 align:middle line:90%
>>DOUILLARD: Well--

00:18:40.570 --> 00:18:41.090 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That's about it?

00:18:41.090 --> 00:18:41.320 align:middle line:90%
No?

00:18:41.320 --> 00:18:42.190 align:middle line:84%
>>DOUILLARD: That's
the number one

00:18:42.190 --> 00:18:44.800 align:middle line:84%
problem is that when people are
used to having meals every two

00:18:44.800 --> 00:18:46.780 align:middle line:84%
to three hours, then
they go to bed and go,

00:18:46.780 --> 00:18:48.110 align:middle line:84%
now we're going to sleep
for eight or nine hours,

00:18:48.110 --> 00:18:49.247 align:middle line:90%
the body goes, what?

00:18:49.247 --> 00:18:50.830 align:middle line:84%
I'm used to being
fed every two hours.

00:18:50.830 --> 00:18:51.790 align:middle line:90%
I need some food.

00:18:51.790 --> 00:18:53.620 align:middle line:90%
So they wake up hungry.

00:18:53.620 --> 00:18:57.580 align:middle line:84%
The second cause of
insomnia in America

00:18:57.580 --> 00:18:59.732 align:middle line:90%
is blood sugar instability.

00:18:59.732 --> 00:19:00.940 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That's fascinating.

00:19:00.940 --> 00:19:02.170 align:middle line:84%
I don't think most
people know that.

00:19:02.170 --> 00:19:02.660 align:middle line:90%
>>DOUILLARD: No.

00:19:02.660 --> 00:19:04.180 align:middle line:84%
So we have to give
the body a reason

00:19:04.180 --> 00:19:07.150 align:middle line:84%
to be a good fat burner,
and not just to lose weight.

00:19:07.150 --> 00:19:09.060 align:middle line:90%
Fat is calm fuel.

00:19:09.060 --> 00:19:10.480 align:middle line:90%
It's stable fuel.

00:19:10.480 --> 00:19:12.070 align:middle line:90%
It's not emergency fuel.

00:19:12.070 --> 00:19:13.610 align:middle line:84%
It's sleep-through-the-night
fuel.

00:19:13.610 --> 00:19:15.400 align:middle line:90%
It's your detoxifying fuel.

00:19:15.400 --> 00:19:17.620 align:middle line:84%
It neutralizes the
acidity in your body

00:19:17.620 --> 00:19:20.380 align:middle line:84%
from all the stress that
makes your body toxic

00:19:20.380 --> 00:19:21.430 align:middle line:90%
and degenerative.

00:19:21.430 --> 00:19:23.650 align:middle line:84%
So if you want your body
to burn fat-- and we do,

00:19:23.650 --> 00:19:25.000 align:middle line:90%
for lots of reasons--

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:26.320 align:middle line:90%
you have to give it a reason.

00:19:26.320 --> 00:19:28.330 align:middle line:90%
Breakfast, nothing till lunch.

00:19:28.330 --> 00:19:30.968 align:middle line:84%
In between breakfast
and lunch, you burn fat.

00:19:30.968 --> 00:19:33.010 align:middle line:84%
If you have a carrot
between breakfast and lunch,

00:19:33.010 --> 00:19:33.780 align:middle line:90%
you're going to burn the carrot.

00:19:33.780 --> 00:19:35.080 align:middle line:90%
And that's the healthy meal.

00:19:35.080 --> 00:19:36.190 align:middle line:90%
Carrots are good for you.

00:19:36.190 --> 00:19:37.240 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But you're not
going to burn the fat.

00:19:37.240 --> 00:19:38.365 align:middle line:90%
>>DOUILLARD: Not that meal.

00:19:38.365 --> 00:19:40.510 align:middle line:84%
From lunch to supper,
I have an apple.

00:19:40.510 --> 00:19:42.400 align:middle line:84%
Well, an apple's
good for you, but I

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:43.910 align:middle line:90%
didn't burn my fat that day.

00:19:43.910 --> 00:19:47.290 align:middle line:84%
And from supper all the way
to breakfast, we burn fat.

00:19:47.290 --> 00:19:50.200 align:middle line:84%
Now when I was a kid,
we had supper at 5:30.

00:19:50.200 --> 00:19:52.330 align:middle line:90%
6 o'clock, kitchen was closed.

00:19:52.330 --> 00:19:54.370 align:middle line:84%
Went out, kicked the
can, come back, play,

00:19:54.370 --> 00:19:56.710 align:middle line:84%
wake up at 7 o'clock,
and have breakfast.

00:19:56.710 --> 00:19:59.907 align:middle line:84%
That was 13 hours of our
day fasting, no food.

00:19:59.907 --> 00:20:02.240 align:middle line:84%
That would be like social
services knocking on your door

00:20:02.240 --> 00:20:04.320 align:middle line:84%
and say, excuse me, Mrs.
Johnson, you're fasting.

00:20:04.320 --> 00:20:05.570 align:middle line:90%
You're starving your children.

00:20:05.570 --> 00:20:06.370 align:middle line:90%
You can't be doing that.

00:20:06.370 --> 00:20:08.010 align:middle line:84%
You gotta feed your
kids every three hours.

00:20:08.010 --> 00:20:08.500 align:middle line:90%
It's America.

00:20:08.500 --> 00:20:08.810 align:middle line:90%
Come on.

00:20:08.810 --> 00:20:09.190 align:middle line:90%
Gotta feed them.

00:20:09.190 --> 00:20:09.860 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: No, that's
how we were raised.

00:20:09.860 --> 00:20:11.320 align:middle line:84%
But you didn't see
obese kids either.

00:20:11.320 --> 00:20:11.800 align:middle line:90%
>>DOUILLARD: No, you didn't.

00:20:11.800 --> 00:20:13.630 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: None of our
friends had obesity.

00:20:13.630 --> 00:20:14.700 align:middle line:84%
I usually say, you're
out playing after dinner.

00:20:14.700 --> 00:20:17.560 align:middle line:84%
>>DOUILLARD: Attention deficit,
asthma, all these issues,

00:20:17.560 --> 00:20:18.730 align:middle line:90%
we just didn't see it.

00:20:18.730 --> 00:20:21.550 align:middle line:84%
So the ability to
be good fat burners

00:20:21.550 --> 00:20:23.920 align:middle line:84%
is the ability to make
energy last and be stable,

00:20:23.920 --> 00:20:25.527 align:middle line:90%
and that creates a stable mood.

00:20:25.527 --> 00:20:27.610 align:middle line:84%
And that's something we
don't have in this country

00:20:27.610 --> 00:20:28.550 align:middle line:90%
either is stable mood.

00:20:28.550 --> 00:20:30.640 align:middle line:84%
Everybody's gone wacky,
and depressed, and anxious.

00:20:30.640 --> 00:20:30.880 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:20:30.880 --> 00:20:32.130 align:middle line:84%
>>DOUILLARD: Can't
handle stress any longer.

00:20:32.130 --> 00:20:32.930 align:middle line:90%
It's a big deal.

00:20:32.930 --> 00:20:35.490 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Now you're on a
drug to manage your moods.

00:20:35.490 --> 00:20:36.500 align:middle line:90%
>>DOUILLARD: Exactly.

00:20:36.500 --> 00:20:36.660 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:20:36.660 --> 00:20:39.160 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And I noticed that a
lot of people that are trying

00:20:39.160 --> 00:20:42.237 align:middle line:84%
to burn the fat, have
gone away from the carbs--

00:20:42.237 --> 00:20:43.320 align:middle line:90%
we've seen a lot of this--

00:20:43.320 --> 00:20:45.840 align:middle line:84%
but there seems to
be these periods

00:20:45.840 --> 00:20:49.980 align:middle line:84%
of really grumpy dispositions,
agitation, irritation.

00:20:49.980 --> 00:20:53.040 align:middle line:84%
And so obviously, that's
not working for them.

00:20:53.040 --> 00:20:56.593 align:middle line:84%
If you're having that, That's
not a normal manifestation.

00:20:56.593 --> 00:20:59.010 align:middle line:84%
If you're having a balanced
diet, that wouldn't be, right?

00:20:59.010 --> 00:21:01.290 align:middle line:84%
>>DOUILLARD: Low-carb diets
are a form of starvation.

00:21:01.290 --> 00:21:04.620 align:middle line:84%
And we burn fat because in the
old days, hunter-gatherers,

00:21:04.620 --> 00:21:06.150 align:middle line:90%
it was feast or famine.

00:21:06.150 --> 00:21:07.560 align:middle line:84%
And we were very
used to starving

00:21:07.560 --> 00:21:09.420 align:middle line:84%
and probably were a
little on the grumpy

00:21:09.420 --> 00:21:10.950 align:middle line:84%
side during that
starvation time.

00:21:10.950 --> 00:21:11.470 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Probably.

00:21:11.470 --> 00:21:12.928 align:middle line:84%
>>DOUILLARD: So
that explains that.

00:21:12.928 --> 00:21:16.380 align:middle line:84%
But what we really
have to try to take

00:21:16.380 --> 00:21:19.710 align:middle line:84%
the stress, the emergency,
out of people's lives.

00:21:19.710 --> 00:21:22.950 align:middle line:84%
People finish their day
exhausted and wasted.

00:21:22.950 --> 00:21:24.820 align:middle line:84%
Their life has
become a struggle.

00:21:24.820 --> 00:21:27.330 align:middle line:84%
And when you start
eating properly,

00:21:27.330 --> 00:21:30.080 align:middle line:84%
you finish your day with the
same energy as you started.

00:21:30.080 --> 00:21:32.320 align:middle line:84%
It's a sign post
of balanced diet.

00:21:32.320 --> 00:21:34.413 align:middle line:84%
If you need meal, snack,
meal, snack, meal,

00:21:34.413 --> 00:21:36.330 align:middle line:84%
snack, throughout the
day, I can guarantee you

00:21:36.330 --> 00:21:37.920 align:middle line:84%
that your blood
sugar's unstable.

00:21:37.920 --> 00:21:41.485 align:middle line:84%
It's one of the first lifestyle
measures that you can take.

00:21:41.485 --> 00:21:43.860 align:middle line:84%
Can you go from breakfast to
lunch, from lunch to supper,

00:21:43.860 --> 00:21:46.027 align:middle line:84%
from supper to bed, with
no snacks and be satisfied?

00:21:46.027 --> 00:21:48.240 align:middle line:84%
If you can, blood
sugar's probably OK.

00:21:48.240 --> 00:21:50.910 align:middle line:84%
If you need that
snack, it's a red flag.

00:21:50.910 --> 00:21:52.560 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And at
the same time, we're

00:21:52.560 --> 00:21:54.750 align:middle line:84%
no longer accustomed
to becoming hungry.

00:21:54.750 --> 00:21:57.357 align:middle line:84%
We don't like the
feeling of hunger.

00:21:57.357 --> 00:21:58.440 align:middle line:90%
>>DOUILLARD: That's right.

00:21:58.440 --> 00:22:00.732 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And so as soon as
you feel your stomach growl

00:22:00.732 --> 00:22:04.620 align:middle line:84%
a little bit, just that first
pang of hunger, in the West--

00:22:04.620 --> 00:22:05.940 align:middle line:90%
well, in America, anyway--

00:22:05.940 --> 00:22:08.060 align:middle line:84%
we tend to throw something
at it right away.

00:22:08.060 --> 00:22:08.860 align:middle line:90%
>>DOUILLARD: Yeah.

00:22:08.860 --> 00:22:13.980 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Now we've conditioned
ourselves to experience hunger

00:22:13.980 --> 00:22:14.820 align:middle line:90%
as a negative.

00:22:14.820 --> 00:22:16.843 align:middle line:90%


00:22:16.843 --> 00:22:18.510 align:middle line:84%
>>DOUILLARD: You bring
up a point there,

00:22:18.510 --> 00:22:21.960 align:middle line:84%
because the sugars
in our foods provide

00:22:21.960 --> 00:22:24.240 align:middle line:84%
a certain sense of
satiety, not only

00:22:24.240 --> 00:22:26.850 align:middle line:84%
for the tummy and the
body, but for the brain.

00:22:26.850 --> 00:22:29.700 align:middle line:84%
And that instant surge
of sugar into the brain

00:22:29.700 --> 00:22:32.910 align:middle line:84%
activates a dopamine receptor,
dopamine in the brain.

00:22:32.910 --> 00:22:36.400 align:middle line:84%
And dopamine is the "I gotta
have it right now" hormone.

00:22:36.400 --> 00:22:38.700 align:middle line:84%
So the brain has been
triggered and used

00:22:38.700 --> 00:22:41.140 align:middle line:84%
to from that first ice
cream as a 3-year-old

00:22:41.140 --> 00:22:43.450 align:middle line:84%
to "I gotta have it
right now" hormone.

00:22:43.450 --> 00:22:45.210 align:middle line:90%
So we have become--

00:22:45.210 --> 00:22:46.860 align:middle line:84%
it's very interesting,
and I've written

00:22:46.860 --> 00:22:48.600 align:middle line:84%
about this in my
newsletters-- we've

00:22:48.600 --> 00:22:51.510 align:middle line:84%
become little junkies,
little drug addicts,

00:22:51.510 --> 00:22:55.760 align:middle line:84%
addicted to a host of dopamine
activators, like shopping.

00:22:55.760 --> 00:22:58.410 align:middle line:84%
When you go shopping,
your dopamine level

00:22:58.410 --> 00:23:02.560 align:middle line:84%
starts to rise, and rise,
and then it goes higher.

00:23:02.560 --> 00:23:04.750 align:middle line:84%
And as you're browsing,
it's getting higher.

00:23:04.750 --> 00:23:06.750 align:middle line:84%
But as soon as you
swipe that card,

00:23:06.750 --> 00:23:07.988 align:middle line:90%
the dopamine levels crash.

00:23:07.988 --> 00:23:09.530 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And that
happens to people.

00:23:09.530 --> 00:23:11.280 align:middle line:84%
I see this with
women all the time.

00:23:11.280 --> 00:23:13.320 align:middle line:90%
They buy this stuff, and then--

